> They will ship.  IBM is in a luxurious position, because putting down
> the Pentium will boost interest in the PPC solution.  IBM competes with
> Intel in this area.  Sounds like a clever move by IBM.  Compaq, Dell, and
> Gateway have no choice but to push those Pentium boxes out.  If not, they
> lose sales, and that stops cash flow.  Of course, they could say no
> Pentiums, 486 instead.  But then, where's the beef?  I also suspect IBM
> was not going to be competitive with their Pentium systems anyway.

Isn't having your customers believe you have integrety and that your
products are reliable more important that a quaterly earnings report. 
Compaq should follow IBMs lead immediately.  They still have plenty of non
Pentium systems to sell and doing so would pay off in the long run. 
Otherwise there are going to be thousands of people who buy Pentium systems
only to discovet that Compaq sold them knowing they were defective and will
not trust them in the future.  Intel knew about the bug in June and
continued to ship systems.  This was highly unethical.   Computer
manufaturers who continue to ship Pentium systems now that they know about
the bug being just as unethical (Unless they stamp every box with a sticker
that says "Warning, defective CPU inside).  I'm sure this reliability issue
is why IBM has discontinued shipping systems.  They want their customers to
be able to believe that IBM would not knowingly sell them a defective
system.  Can the Compaq afford to do any less?

